1. Read Data & Create Time Series

# Read data from csv into R
spower.data <- read.csv("solar-energy-consumption.csv") 
# data from 1985 to 2020

#filter data
spower.world.data <- spower.data[spower.data$Entity == "World",]
spower.us.data <- spower.data[spower.data$Entity == "United States",]
spower.china.data <- spower.data[spower.data$Entity == "China",]
# create time series -- World
spower.world.ts <- ts(spower.world.data$Electricity.from.solar..TWh., start = c(1985), end = c(2020), frequency = 1)

# create time series -- United States
co2.us.ts <- ts(spower.us.data$Electricity.from.solar., start = c(1985), end = c(2020), frequency = 1)

# create time series -- China
co2.china.ts <- ts(spower.china.data$Electricity.from.solar., start = c(1985), end = c(2020), frequency = 1)

================================================================================= ### 2. World Data

# split data - approximately 70% training data, 30% validation data
spower.world.train <- window(spower.world.ts, start = c(1985), end = c(2016))
spower.world.valid <- window(spower.world.ts, start = c(2017))
#check the length of each
length(spower.world.train)
## [1] 32
length(spower.world.valid)
## [1] 4
nValid = 4
World Solar Energy Plot
autoplot(spower.world.ts, xlab = "Year", ylab = "World Solar Energy")

Simple Models Plots: Naive, Mean, Random Walk with drift
autoplot(spower.world.train, xlab = "Year", ylab = "World Solar Energy") +
    autolayer(meanf(spower.world.train, h = 21), 
              series = "Mean", PI = FALSE) +
    autolayer(naive(spower.world.train, h = 21),
              series = "Naive", PI = FALSE) +
    autolayer(rwf(spower.world.train, drift = TRUE, h = 21),
              series = "Drift", PI = FALSE) +
    guides(colour = guide_legend(title = "Forecast"))

I. Regression

(1) Quadratic Model
# fit linear model
world.quad <- tslm(spower.world.train ~ trend + I(trend^2))
summary(world.quad)

# summary of performance

Regression Models Comparison

reg.result <- data.frame(
    Regression.Model  = c("Quadratic", "Fourth Order", "Fifth Order", "Exponential"),
    RMSE = c(world.quad.rmse, world.fourth.rmse, world.fifth.rmse, world.exp.rmse))

Fourth Order performs the best among all regression models.

II. Exponential Smoothing Model

#automated smoothing model
world.ses <- ets(spower.world.train, model = "ZZZ", restrict = FALSE, allow.multiplicative.trend = TRUE)
world.ses
## ETS(M,A,N) 
## 
## Call:
##  ets(y = spower.world.train, model = "ZZZ", restrict = FALSE,  
## 
##  Call:
##      allow.multiplicative.trend = TRUE) 
## 
##   Smoothing parameters:
##     alpha = 0.5058 
##     beta  = 0.4073 
## 
##   Initial states:
##     l = -0.5586 
##     b = 0.047 
## 
##   sigma:  0.4167
## 
##      AIC     AICc      BIC 
## 118.0450 120.3527 125.3737
world.ses.pred <- forecast(world.ses , h = nValid, level = 0)
plot(world.ses.pred, ylab = "Solar Energy", xlab = "Year", 
     bty = "l", main = "World Solar Energy w/ Smoothing Model", flty = 2, xlim =c(1980, 2025))

lines(world.ses.pred$fitted, lwd = 2, col ="blue")
lines(spower.world.ts)

result_ses <- accuracy(world.ses.pred$mean, spower.world.valid)
result_ses
##                ME     RMSE      MAE      MPE     MAPE      ACF1 Theil's U

world.ses.rmse <- result_ses[2]
